2023 is the year Knitted Wit turns 16!

So many of the songs and sayings about turning "Sweet Sixteen" are gross and misogynistic, so we're just going to lean into the sweetness and say, we cannot believe this little yarn baby that spent so much time in my back yard is 16 whole years old! It feels a bit overwhelming and incomprehensible to be hitting this milestone, friends! We'll be celebrating all year long, in the best way we can: with yarn and community!

We are running a very special special on our Targhee bases, and y’all! This palette is so soft yet deep, so flirty yet sophisticated. We are, in a word, smitten.

We’ve got 2 different weights of Targhee available. Both are the same sheep-to-skein US Targhee wool, and one is a DK-to-Worsted (280 yards in a 4-ounce skein), while the other is a Worsted-to-Aran (210 yards to a 4-ounce skein). Because of the nature of this yarn, it’s got a lot of range; the yarn can be squished down to a denser fabric while retaining its softness and drape, and can also be worked at a slightly looser gauge without losing its structure. 

We’re hosting a very loosey-goosey, no-rules make-a-long for the next few months. We’re leaning toward sweaters, because we are chilly-willy these days, but you can make whatever your maker heart desires. And the best thing? The yarn is being offered at a special price: $25 a skein instead of $30! 

Head to our Etsy shop to snag some skeins of fab yarn right now, and use the hashtag #knittedwittargheemal to share your project with us!

It’s Throwback Thursday, friends, and as a part of our year-long celebration of Knitted Wit’s Sweet Sixteen, we are sharing some vintage colorways every month. Since we are deep in the season of love (Palentine’s Day, Galentine’s Day, and Valentine’s Day), we are sharing some of our favorite LOVEly colors! 

The four we chose to focus on all have special meaning:

Third Grade Valentine is the Valentine’s color of our elementary school dreams! It’s all pinks and reds and whites, and is the exact color of the Valentine’s box we made in the 3rd grade…

Galentine’s Day is our homage to Leslie Knope of fave show Parks and Rec and her commitment to friendship. 

Palentine’s Day is our homage to a more inclusive update to Galentine’s Day, and the holiday and vibe we are celebrating at our Open Studio party this Sunday (it’s from 10-4, come on by!)

And finally, February 23rd is the day your dried-out Val/Gal/Palentine’s Day flowers look like this skein (we are quite tickled with this one, even if we have to explain it to everyone, always). 

Which colorway most speaks to your perfect Val/Gal/Palentine’s Day? They are all listed in the shop, and are available on all of our bases.

We are slowly expanding our hours too, and this week, for the first time, we are open 4 whole days!

🌿🌲🏕️ It's that time of the year again! We've loaded up the car with our tents, our craft projects, and enough snacks to sustain an entire wolf pack. We're headed to Camp Knitted Wit for some much-needed outdoor fun and relaxation.

But before we hit the trails, we're playing along with some Vacay Bingo. We're already ahead of the game with our iced beverages in hand! Can we get a "Bingo!" before the summer is over?

Whether you're exploring a National Park, your local park, or just your own backyard, make sure to bring your favorite projects and join us in the great outdoors this year. You never know what kind of wildlife (or yarn) you might discover! 🌲🌿🏕️

It’s one of our absolute favorite times of the year, friends, PARKS TIME! Every year, from May through August, we partner with LYS’s to take a tour through the natural spaces in the US with our National Parks Club! There are so many wonderful places to explore, and we figure, if we can’t get to every one in person, at least we’ll venture there in yarn, right?

Our first 4 parks (photo 1), which are being shared at many LYSs across the country, are:
*Montezuma Castle National Monument in Arizona (photo 2);
*Anacostia Park in Washington, DC (the only roller rink in the National Parks system!) (photo 3);
*Craters of the Moon National Monument & Preserve in Idaho (photo 4); and
*Martin Luther King National Historic Park in Atlanta, Georgia (photo 5).

The ONLY place you can get these gorgeous skeins is at one of our participating LYS’s, listed on our website. While there, snag a postcard so you can earn a patch (buy 4 skeins through the summer) or a pin (buy 16 skeins through the summer), and a VACAY BINGO card. We’ve got lots of fun things planned for the summer, so let’s get our knit/crochet on, friends!

As y’all get our 2023 National Parks making figured out, don’t forget about our popular Socks & Hats on Vacay! We’ve been doing this make along for quite a few years now, and hope you’ll take part! @shannonsq is offering a 25% discount on all of her patterns, both on Ravelry & Payhip, so use code SUMMERTIME23 to get that deal, and share photos of your socks and hats on Instagram, tagging both of us and using hashtag #sockshatsvacay to be entered to win a prize at the end of the summer!

Plus, we are once again playing some Vacay Bingo! Snag a copy of our Bingo card at your Parks Club-participating LYS, here at the @craftemmporiumpdx during our open hours, or download it on our website, linked in profile, and play all summer long! All participants will get a little something-something for their efforts, plus we’ll choose a winner or to to get a skein of yarn at the end of the summer!

For all details and to check out the list of participating shops, head to our profile (or our website, knittedwit.com). We are so excited to see what you’ll make this summer!

Most of us have heard of the Bechdel Test, which is a measure of the representation of women in film and other works of art/media. The test evaluates whether or not a work of fiction portrays women in a way that is sexist or characterized by gender stereotyping. To pass the Bechdel test, there are three rules: the work must feature at least two women; these women must talk to each other; and their conversation must concern something other than a man. Many pieces of modern media fail this test miserably. This way of measuring a work’s patriarchal inclinations was created by famed lesbian cartoonist Alison Bechdel, who is our HerStory recipient for June.

Our colorway, Passing the Test, was inspired by a rainbow created from an image from Dykes to Watch Out For, because a rainbow would certainly pass our test.

Read the whole Love Letter, with more information about Alison Bechdel and the test that bears her name, on our blog, and snag this gorgeous yarn from one of our LYS partners, also linked on our website!

Every year, we fall more and more in love with our National Parks Club yarns, the places we feature, and the Socks & Hats on Vacay make-along we host all summer long. Not to mention the fun challenge of creating 16 unique colorways throughout the summer that pay homage to these natural spaces we all love. 

For June, we’re traveling to Bandelier National Monument near Los Alamos in New Mexico (photos 2-3); Fire Island National Seashore in Suffolk County, New York (photos 4-5); Oregon Caves National Monument and Preserve in the northern Siskiyou Mountains of southwestern Oregon (photos 6-7); and Tallgrass Prairie National Preserve in the Flint Hills region of Kansas (photos 8-9). Check out the lovely skeins and tubes we created from each of them, and go to our website to read the full article about these natural spaces, including information about the indigenous people on whose ancestral lands each space occupies. You can also find information on our website about our LYS partners, where you can get your hands on this yarn (and work toward earning a patch or pin at the end of the summer). Plus our fun Vacay Bingo is back, and you can download the bingo form there as well!

We love romance here at Knitted Wit World HQ, and Talia Hibbert (@taliahibbert) is at the top of our fave romance writers. Her Brown Sisters trilogy is one we revisit at least once a year, and the representation of her characters is just plain amazeballs. Talia Hibbert herself identifies across multiple spectrums of marginalization: she’s a Black woman, queer, disabled, and on the autism spectrum, so her books and characters are filled with representation and inclusion. Plus, they are delightfully spicy (although she published her first YA book earlier this year, spiceless and still as sweet and wonderful as her other books). 

The colorway we created (Take a Hint) is, once again, delicious (geez, are we hungry or what?), and we can’t wait to make some cuddly socks out of it. 

Head to our shop to sign up for HerStory, or hit our blog to find out if your LYS carries it. Read and craft with us as we spend a bit of time with Talia Hibbert this summer!

Fat Bear Week is getting started! We wanted to share a few of our favorite colors from our National Park series, starting with Kobuk Valley! If you want to know more about our parks series, check out our blog. You can search for any park and see what we’ve created! 

Whose land does this National Park reside upon?
Kobuk Valley National Park has been home to humans for as long as there have been people on this continent. During the last Ice Age, the valley remained free of ice and teamed with big game, including the woolly mammoth. Some of America’s very first inhabitants called Kobuk Valley their home. At a wide bend in the Kobuk River called Onion Portage, archeologists have found evidence that for at least 9,000 years, the caribou herd has been crossing the river there during their annual migrations. For just as long, humans have been gathering there to hunt them. Local Inupiaq Eskimos still hunt the caribou as they cross the Kobuk River at Onion Portage, just as their ancestors have done for ten thousand years. 
When was it established as a National Park?
December 2, 1980
Why is this park amazing?
Kobuk Valley National Park is home to a rich and varied landscape. The mighty boreal forest reaches its northern limits here before giving way to the rolling expanse of the arctic tundra, creating an open woodland of birch and spruce carpeted with moss and caribou lichen. The park is bisected by the Kobuk River, which slowly meanders its way across the landscape for 61 miles. To the north of the river stretch the peaks of the Baird Mountains, while to the south lie the Great Kobuk Sand Dunes, the largest active sand dunes in the Arctic. Half a million caribou migrate through, their tracks crisscrossing sculpted dunes.
Why did we choose these colors?
The photo we chose to recreate in our Kobuk Valley skein shows the wide open sky, peppered with heavy clouds, over the sand dune’y valley. The mountains beckon in the distance. The skein mixes those blue-greys and browns in the most delightful way.

We’re visiting another park in Alaska, this one a bit closer to where all the bear action is! 

Where is it located?

Aniakchak National Monument and Preserve is located about 450 miles/720 km southwest of Anchorage on the Alaskan Peninsula. 

Whose land does it reside upon?

Archeologists believe that the massive volcanic eruption that occurred 3500 years ago created a “dead zone” that couldn’t be reoccupied for generations. The oldest known archeological sites date to around 2,000 years ago, and showed prehistoric communities that hunted, fished, trapped, picked berries, and gathered shellfish. By 1,200 years ago, the strategy had proven so successful that the population had expanded dramatically, and eventually segued into a community that utilized the land’s rich fishing resources to build a commercial fishing and canning industry. The modern Alutiiq people descended from the early inhabitants of Aniakchak, and continue to maintain cultural traditions.

When was it established?

December 1, 1978

Why is it amazing?

Given its remote location and challenging weather conditions, Aniakchak is one of the most wild and least visited places in the National Park System. The landscape is a vibrant reminder of Alaska’s location in the volcanically active “Ring of Fire,” as it is home to an impressive six mile/10 km wide, 2,500 ft/762 m deep caldera formed during a massive volcanic eruption 3,500 years ago. In 2018, only 100 people visited, likely because it is so very isolated. Much of the National Monument is not accessible by road, and the only way to reach much of it is by floatplane, boat, or airplane to coastal towns near preserve lands followed by overland or overwater traverse.

Why did we choose these colors?

Flip through the scant images on the NPS website and you’ll surely see why we chose these colors: the clear blue of the mountain lakes set against the soft greys and greens of the mountains in the caldera are perfectly echoed in our Aniakchak colorway.

Another beautiful park in Alaska!
Where is this park located: 
Lake Clark National Park is located in southwest Alaska, about 100 miles southwest of Anchorage.

Whose land does this National Park reside upon?

people first came to the Lake Clark region around the end of the last ice age. Dena’ina, Yup’ik, and Sugpiaq peoples. The Dena’ina people have called Qizhjeh Vena, also known as Lake Clark, home for thousands of years, and still reside here, living with and off the land, and working to preserve their culture.

When was it established as a National Park?

December 2, 1980

Why is this park amazing?

Volcanoes steam, salmon run, bears forage, and craggy mountains reflect in shimmering turquoise lakes. Here, too, local people and culture still depend on the land and water. Lake Clark preserves the ancestral homelands of the Dena’ina people, an intact ecosystem at the headwaters of the largest sockeye salmon fishery in the world, and a rich cultural wilderness.

Why did we choose these colors?

With a park name of Lake Clark, OF COURSE we’re going to showcase the lake and the area surrounding it for our colorway. Rich blues and greens run through the skein, making us all want to jump in a lake in celebration.

We’re still traveling around Alaska looking at Parks in honor of Fat Bear Week! 
Where is it located?

Extreme Northwestern Alaska.

Whose land does it reside upon?

From the NPS website: 

“Many of the stories told about Bering Land Bridge National Preserve are focused on its prehistory, but the more recent past and present-day cultural traditions of Northwest Alaska are just as important. Deeply-rooted cultural practices and traditional subsistence hunting and gathering are still a part of everyday life for most Inupiaq communities around the Seward Peninsula. The protection of resources within Bering Land Bridge helps to support these lifestyles, as well as communicate to others the importance of Alaska Native heritage in a holistic context.

Today’s cultural groups of the Seward Peninsula remain closely tied to the ancestors who first crossed over from Siberia, and many still have living relatives on the Asian side of the Bering Strait. Up until European contact in the 19th century, these groups led mobile subsistence lifestyles, moving seasonally with food availability and thriving off the land and the sea.”

When was it established?

December 1, 1978

About this park:

The Bering Land Bridge National Preserve is one of the most remote United States national park areas, located on the Seward Peninsula. The National Preserve protects a remnant of the Bering Land Bridge that connected Asia with North America more than 13,000 years ago during the Pleistocene ice age, that many geologists, paleontologists, and other scientists believe was the path to the population of the americas.

One of our goals for this year is to post here more consistently, and to share some of our colorways that maybe we haven’t shared (or haven’t shared in a while). Monday will be HerStory day, and today, we’re sharing our current HerStory colorway. This year, we’re focusing on flowers, and telling stories about women inspired by flowers.

January’s colorway is Lily of the Valley, inspired by the lovely flowers that are the birth-month flowers of our HerStory recipient, Sylvia Robinson. Robinson is known as the Mother of Hip-Hop: she was the founder and CEO of Sugar Hill records AND the producer and promoter of two of the most iconic songs in hip-hop history, Rapper’s Delight (1979) by the Sugarhill Gang, and The Message (1982) by Grandmaster Flash and the Furious Five. In a discovery that tickled our fancy even more, she’s the Sylvia from the “Sylvia? Yes Mickey? How do you call your loverboy?” song from Dirty Dancing! AND! She played guitar on and arranged Ike & Tina Turner’s first hit, It’s Gonna Work Out Fine (but did not get a producer credit, because patriarchy).
Oh my goodness it went off the rails a bit. We talk about our vision boards, new projects, lorajean gets derailed on quilted hexi’s, and we talk about Sustaining Circle!!

This past year has been hard, y’all! It’s been hard for a lot of small businesses, and we are no exception. We’ve been brainstorming ways to keep on keeping on, and one exciting idea we came up with (with a LOT of input from other small biz friends) is this: the Friends of Knitted Wit’s Craft Emporium Membership. If you want to accomplish both the goals of seeing Knitted Wit & Craft Emporium survive, even thrive, AND have access to awesome patterns, how-tos, discounts, and private virtual hangs with awesome people, consider joining the club! 

We’re modeling this (sorta, kinda) on the NPR Sustaining Circle membership, and have created a membership on our website so y’all can sign up easily. There are different levels of membership, and the membership renews every month. You can opt in and out whenever you’d like, and we super appreciate any way you can support us, including sharing with your friends and fellow crafty folk.
